<h3>Flavor Profiles and Structure</h3>

<p>Chardonnay's flavor spectrum ranges dramatically based on winemaking techniques. Unoaked versions showcase pure fruit—crisp green apple, Asian pear, and citrus zest—while oak-aged expressions develop rich vanilla, butterscotch, and toasted almond notes through malolactic fermentation and lees stirring. The grape's naturally lower acidity allows for fuller body and rounder mouthfeel.</p>

<p>Sauvignon Blanc maintains consistent high acidity and aromatic intensity regardless of origin. Its signature herbaceous character stems from methoxypyrazines, the same compounds found in bell peppers. Cool-climate expressions emphasize mineral-driven citrus and grass notes, while warmer regions produce tropical fruit flavors like passion fruit and guava, balanced by that characteristic zingy acidity.</p>

<h3>When to Choose Each</h3>

<p><strong>Choose Chardonnay</strong> when you want versatility and complexity. It excels with rich, creamy dishes, roasted chicken, or lobster thermidor. The wine's broader body and potential oak influence make it ideal for special occasions and contemplative sipping.</p>

<p><strong>Choose Sauvignon Blanc</strong> for refreshing simplicity and food-friendly acidity. It's perfect for summer entertaining, seafood platters, or any dish featuring herbs and citrus. Its bright, clean profile makes it an excellent aperitif.</p>

<h3>Substitution Guidelines</h3>

<p>These wines rarely substitute well for each other due to fundamental structural differences. Sauvignon Blanc's piercing acidity and herbaceous notes can't replicate Chardonnay's richness, while Chardonnay lacks the bright, food-cutting qualities that make Sauvignon Blanc essential for certain pairings. However, unoaked Chardonnay can sometimes bridge the gap in situations calling for medium-bodied white wine with good acidity.</p>

